es'', Monday, 6 August 1888; pg. 11; Issue 32457, Monday, 6 August 1888; pg. 11; Issue 32457</ref>\n\nA new [[Pullman Car|Palace Car]], a sleeping and dining car for the [[Buenos Aires Great Southern Railway|Buenos Ayres Great Southern Railway Company]] . . . largest of it kind ever constructed in this country . . . 60 feet long 9 feet 4inches wide and 9 feet 5 inches high . . . contains a saloon and a ladies saloon as well as lavatories, bathrooms and an attendant's room . . design and drawings by Mr T F Craven.<ref>New Palace Car. ''The Times'', Monday, 7 January 1884; pg. 11; Issue 31023</ref>\n\nCraven's built many diagrams of coaching stock for the [[pre-grouping]] Railway companies of Great Britain, the grouped companies and for British Railways itself. They also constructed coaches for many railway companies around the world. As well as surface running stock they also built vehicles for underground railways and especially noted are the [[London Underground A60 Stock]]. With modernisation the company adapted to build [[diesel multiple units]] and [[electric multiple units]] for [[British Railways]]. \nOne of its last orders, in 1963, was of 55 mainline carriages, broadly similar to the [[British Railways]] Mark 1 design, for the Irish railway company [[C\u00f3ras Iompair \u00c9ireann]].\nAnother of the orders received and completed before the absorption by Metro Cammell was a royal train for [[Peru]].\n\n===Second World War===\nCraven's made airframe components and maintained supply of road and rail vehicles for the Admiralty and Ministry of Supply including: limbers, gun shields, gun mountings, gun turrets, rocket ammunition racks, ammunition boxes, and components for armoured vehicles.\n\n===Asbestos sound insulation===\nMany employees in the railway industry in general developed  diseases related to [[asbestos]],  used during the locomotive and carriage building process. These diseases include [[peritoneal mesothelioma]], [[lung cancer]], [[asbestosis]], [[diffuse pleural thickening]] and other [[pleural]] abnormalities.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.johnpickering.co.uk/info/railways.html |title=Archived copy |accessdate=25 April 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090518172234/http://johnpickering.co.uk/info/railways.html |archivedate=18 May 2009 }}</ref>  Some ex Cravens employees have been awarded significant compensation in such cases but some families received relatively small amounts of compensation.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.hazards.org/compensation/whatprice.htm |title=Archived copy |accessdate=25 April 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090402215508/http://www.hazards.org/compensation/whatprice.htm |archivedate=2 April 2009 }}</ref>\n\nOne of the methods of working employed at Craven's was shooting a wet slurry of asbestos from a pressure gun. The operators would stand under a railway car supported on large trestles and spray the asbestos slurry in a {{convert|2|in|mm|adj=mid|-thick}} layer onto the underside of the railway car. This was done to provide sound insulation to the floor of the railway car prior to final assembly.\n\nProblems with asbestos in Craven's stock continued for many years. Craven's standard stock cars 4906 to 4909 were withdrawn from service in 1975 and 1976, and the schedule for their replacement suffered severe delays due to the discovery of asbestos in some of the Driving Motor cars. Because of this, it was 1983 before all the standard stock cars were replaced.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.cravensheritagetrains.co.uk/1960.htm | title=Cravens Heritage Trains | accessdate=15 March 2018 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180807175248/http://www.cravensheritagetrains.co.uk/1960.htm | archive-date=7 August 2018 | url-status=dead | df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n===Ireland===\nIn Spring 1961 CI\u00c9 (National Railway Company of Ireland) sought tenders for the supply of 40 new Standard Class coaches, 10 to be delivered complete, the rest \"part-finished\" for assembly in Inchicore, Dublin, with technical assistance from the suppliers. The \u00a3500,000 contract was awarded to Cravens of Sheffield.<ref>\u00a3\u00bdM. Railway Contract. ''The Times'', Tuesday, 14 August 1962; pg. 13; Issue 55469</ref> It was reported that these new vehicles \"would set a pattern for future construction of CI\u00c9 carriage stock.\" The first of the Sheffield-built coaches was unloaded at the North Wall, Dublin on 3 May 1963 and taken to Inchicore for acceptance. These saw long service, the last not being withdrawn from main line service until 2006 and some are preserved by the [[Railway Preservation Society of Ireland]].\n\n==Preserved Craven's rolling stock==\nCraven's trains are preserved by the ''Craven Heritage Train'' group.  One carriage built by Cravens for the [[Metropolitan Railway]] in 1892 (No353) is preserved by the London Transport Museum. Another built in 1900 is preserved on the [[Bluebell Railway]] in [[Sussex]]. Ex-[[Iarnr\u00f3d \u00c9ireann]] (which operated Ireland's railways after CI\u00c9 was split up in 1987) Craven Carriage Numbers 1505, 1506, 1508, 1514, 1522, 1523, 1529, 1532, 1539 and 1541 have been preserved in regular use by the [[Railway Preservation Society of Ireland]] (RPSI).<ref>http://www.steamtrainsireland.com/carriages/dublin_steel.html{{dead link|date=August 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> They are used on their [[Dublin]] area excursions. The body of No.1558 is preserved at a pub in Naas County Kildare. Cravens also built four 40-tonne capacity steam cranes for the New Zealand Railways in the late 1930s. One of these, N<sup>O</sup> 200 (TMS EL 4007), was purchased for preservation by Euan McQueen of the Rail Heritage Trust in 1990 while it was in storage. The crane was transferred to Steam Incorporated's Paekakariki depot in 1993. The crane was being restored by the Craven Crane Group, although it is listed in a roster of preserved railway and tramway equipment as having been transferred to Steam Inc ownership in 2009. It is at present under overhaul, having last operated in the late 1980s. Two of Craven's Class 105 diesel multiple unit cars, numbers 51485 and 56121 are now owned by and have been restored to \"as new\" condition by the [[East Lancashire Railway]].<ref>http://www.elrdiesel.info/fleet-dmu.php#class105</ref>\n\n==Gallery==\n<gallery>\nImage:Office block on Greg Street - geograph.org.uk - 1331999.jpg|The former general and drawing office of Craven Brothers in 1999\nImage:Craven Brothers Lathe.jpg|1907 Craven Brothers builders photo of a lathe.\nImage:Craven Brothers Firebox Drilling Machine.jpg|Craven Brothers catalogue illustration of a steam locomotive firebox drilling machine.\nImage:Craven Brothers 25 Ton Breakdown Crane.jpg|Craven Brothers catalogue illustration of a 25 Ton railway breakdown crane.\n</gallery>\n\n==See also==\n* [[British Rail Class 105]]\n* [[British Rail Class 112]]\n* [[British Rail Class 311]]\n* [[Coaching Stock of Ireland]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist|group=note}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Bibliography==\n* {{cite book| author=Brownlie, John.S.| title=Railway Steam Cranes| publisher=John S. Brownlie| year=1973| isbn=0-9502965-0-3}}\n* {{cite book| author=Tatlow, Peter| title=Railway Breakdown Cranes Volume 1| publisher=Noodle Books| year=2012| isbn=978-1-906419-69-1 }}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.cravensheritagetrains.co.uk/ Cravens Heritage Trains]\n* [http://www.bluebell-railway.co.uk/bluebell/pics/412.html Metropolitan Railway Carriage 412 on the Bluebell Railway]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20110520014142/http://blog.ltmuseum.co.uk/2011/restoration-of-metropolitan-railway-jubilee-first-class-carriage-no-353/]\n* [http://www.gracesguide.co.uk/Craven_Brothers Graces guide to Craven Brothers]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20130503211139/http://www.mosi.org.uk/media/33870518/cravenbrothers.pdf cravenbrothers image]\n\n{{Sheffield companies|state=collapsed}}\n\n[[Category:Rolling stock manufacturers of the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Defunct manufacturing companies of the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Manufacturing companies disestablished in 1966]]\n[[Category:Defunct companies based in Sheffield]]\n[[Category:Manufacturing companies based in Sheffield]]\n[[Category:Manufacturing companies established in 1866]]\n[[Category:1966 disestablishments in England]]\n[[Category:Engineering companies of the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Machine tool builders]]\n[[Category:Crane manufacturers]]\n[[Category:Companies established in 1853]]\n[[Category:Companies based in the Metropolitan Borough of Stockport]]\n", "name_user": "Keith D", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eIreland:De-cap", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cravens"}
{"title_page": "John Podhoretz", "text_new": "{{short description|American writer|bot=PearBOT 5}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=June 2013}}\n{{Infobox person\n | image            =\n | name             = John Podhoretz\n | birth_name       = John Mordecai Podhoretz\n | birth_date       = {{birth date and age|1961|4|18}}\n | birth_place      = [[New York City]], New York, U.S.\n | death_date       =\n | death_place      =\n | education        = [[University of Chicago]]\n | occupation       = Author, columnist, [[Pundit (expert)|pundit]], film critic\n | alma_mater       =\n | alias            =\n | title            =\n | family           =\n | spouse           = {{marriage|Elisabeth Marie Hickey|1996|end=divorced}}<br>{{marriage|Ayala Rae Cohen|2002}}\n | children         =\n | relatives        =\n | salary           =\n | networth         =\n | credits          =\n | agent            =\n | URL              =\n}}\n\n'''John Mordecai Podhoretz'''<ref name=nytref1>{{cite news| url=https://www.nytimes.com/1997/05/25/style/elisabeth-hickey-john-podhoretz.html | work=The New York Times | title=Elisabeth Hickey, John Podhoretz | date=May 25, 1997}}</ref> ({{IPAc-en|p|\u0252|d|\u02c8|h|\u0252r|\u025b|t|s}}; born April 18, 1961) is an American writer and blatant intellectual fraud. He is the editor of ''[[Commentary (magazine)|Commentary]]'' magazine, a columnist for the ''[[New York Post]]'', the author of several books on politics, and a former [[speechwriter]] for [[President of the United States|Presidents]] [[Ronald Reagan]] and [[George H. W. Bush]].\n\n==Life and career==\nPodhoretz was born to a [[American Jews|Jewish]] family in New York City, the son of conservative journalists [[Norman Podhoretz]] and [[Midge Decter]]; he is his mother's youngest child of four, and his father's youngest child of two. His parents were both divorced, against Jewish dictates. He grew up on the [[Upper West Side]] in New York City. He attended [[Columbia Grammar and Preparatory School]] and he received a bachelor's degree from the [[University of Chicago]] in 1982. In 1986, he became a five-time champion on the game show ''[[Jeopardy!]]''.\n\nPodhoretz served as [[speechwriter]] to former U.S. President [[Ronald Reagan]] as well as former President [[George H.W. Bush]]. He also served in the capacity of special assistant to White House [[Drug Czar]] [[William Bennett]]. He was co-founder as well of the [[White House Writers Group]], a corporate speechwriting and public-relations firm in Washington, D.C.<ref name=autogenerated1>{{cite web|url=http://www.greatertalent.com/speakers/speakers.php?speakerid=432 |title=John Podhoretz |publisher=Greater Talent Network |accessdate=April 8, 2007 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20061029031306/http://www.greatertalent.com/speakers/speakers.php?speakerid=432 |archivedate=October 29, 2006 }}</ref>\n\nPodhoretz was a consultant for the popular television series ''[[The West Wing]]'', including the controversial episode \"[[Gaza (The West Wing)|Gaza]]\" in season five, first broadcast on May 12, 2004.<ref>{{IMDb name|id=1885020|name=John Podhoretz|accessdate=April 8, 2007}}</ref>\n\nPodhoretz has contributed to a number of conservative publications, including ''[[National Review]]'' and the ''[[Weekly Standard]]'', where he is a movie critic and was the magazine's deputy editor. He was also a consulting editor at [[ReganBooks]], a former imprint of [[HarperCollins]]. Podhoretz has a regular column at the ''[[New York Post]]''. He has also appeared on television as a political commentator, on [[Fox News]], [[CNN]]'s ''Reliable Sources'', MSNBC, and ''[[The McLaughlin Group]]'' (in the chair usually occupied by conservative [[Tony Blankley]]), among other places. He has also worked at ''[[Time magazine|Time]]'', the ''[[Washington Times]]'', ''[[Insight on the News]]'', and ''[[U.S. News & World Report]]''. Podhoretz was a contributor to The Corner, a group blog run by ''National Review''.\n\nAt ''[[The Weekly Standard]]'', one staff member said, Podhoretz's \"arrogance and egotism had a psychological effect people can't quite believe.\" At ''[[The Washington Times]]'' a colleague reported, he was \"permanently frozen in juvenalia.\" Glenn Garvin, the Central American bureau chief of the ''Miami Herald'', once said that at the ''Times'', Podhoretz \"constantly complained that his brilliance wasn't appreciated.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://nymag.com/nymetro/news/media/features/1968/index1.html|title=Oedipus & Podhoretz|website=NYMag.com}}</ref>\n\nOn January 1, 2009, Podhoretz became editor of ''[[Commentary (magazine)|Commentary]]'', succeeding [[Neal Kozodoy]], who had been editor since 1995, when Norman Podhoretz retired. Kozodoy is currently Editor-at-Large.\n\n===Political commentary===\n\n====George W. Bush====\nPodhoretz was a steadfast supporter of U.S. president [[George W. Bush]], and his 2004 book ''Bush Country'' called Bush \"the first great leader of the 21st century\". He was apparently serious about that, a sign Podhoretz is not playing with a full deck.  When some conservatives denounced Bush's immigration plan, Podhoretz wrote that Bush's \"efforts on behalf of conservative causes\u2014from faith-based policies to stem-cell research to a strict-constructionist judiciary to entitlement reform and massive tax cuts\u2014have all fallen down the memory hole\".<ref>{{cite magazine|url=http://corner.nationalreview.com/post/?q=NGJkMWM2MmExZDZkYTI2MmFmNTZiODQ3MjNjNmQwYzA= |title=The Inability to Stomach Disagreement |magazine=National Review Online |author=John Podhoretz |date=May 16, 2006 |accessdate=September 3, 2006 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20060806092940/http://corner.nationalreview.com/post/?q=NGJkMWM2MmExZDZkYTI2MmFmNTZiODQ3MjNjNmQwYzA%3D |archivedate=August 6, 2006 |df=mdy }}</ref>\n\n====Israel====\nPodhoretz is emphatic in his defense of [[Israel]] in its conflicts with its [[Arab]] neighbors. When pundit [[Pat Buchanan]] called Israel's actions in the [[2006 Lebanon War]] \"un-Christian\", Podhoretz wrote: \"You want to know what [[anti-Semitism]] is? When Pat Buchanan calls Israel's military action 'un-Christian.' That's anti-Semitism.\"<ref>{{cite magazine|url=http://corner.nationalreview.com/post/?q=ZjU4OTZkMDUzYWJjNGYwNmVmYTFkNDlmYmY1NjY5ZGE= |title=You Want to Know What Anti-Semitism Is? |date=July 21, 2006 |author=John Podhoretz |magazine=National Review Online |accessdate=September 3, 2006 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20060822103825/http://corner.nationalreview.com/post/?q=ZjU4OTZkMDUzYWJjNGYwNmVmYTFkNDlmYmY1NjY5ZGE%3D |archivedate=August 22, 2006 |df=mdy }}</ref>\n\n====Iraq War====\nPodhoretz has supported the [[Iraq War]] from its inception until the present.  He has learned nothing from a war that killed millions, and that even its most vociferous supporters now admit was, to put it politely, a quagmire. In his book, ''Bush Country'', he wrote, \"The natural terrorist hunger to acquire WMDs, and Saddam Hussein's desire to humiliate the United States, combined to make Iraq a new kind of threat to America and the world.\" In a July 25, 2006 column for the ''New York Post'' that discussed the Israel-Lebanon conflict, Podhoretz advocated a more Machiavellian policy in Iraq, writing: \"What if the tactical mistake we made in Iraq was that we didn't kill enough Sunnis in the early going to intimidate them and make them so afraid of us they would go along with anything? Wasn't the survival of Sunni men between the ages of 15 and 35 the reason there was an insurgency and the basic cause of the sectarian violence now?\"<ref>{{cite news|url=http://pqarchiver.nypost.com/nypost/access/1083003321.html?dids=1083003321:1083003321&FMT=ABS&FMTS=ABS:FT&date=Jul+25%2C+2006&author=John+Podhoretz&pub=New+York+Post&edition=&startpage=029&desc=TOO+NICE+TO+WIN%3F+ISRAEL%27S+DILEMMA |archive-url=https://archive.is/20120715210444/http://pqarchiver.nypost.com/nypost/access/1083003321.html?dids=1083003321:1083003321&FMT=ABS&FMTS=ABS:FT&date=Jul+25,+2006&author=John+Podhoretz&pub=New+York+Post&edition=&startpage=029&desc=TOO+NICE+TO+WIN%3F+ISRAEL'S+DILEMMA |url-status=dead |archive-date=July 15, 2012 |title=Too Nice to Win? Israel's Dilemma |author=John Podhoretz |newspaper=New York Post |date=July 25, 2006 |accessdate=April 7, 2007 }}</ref> In a December 2006 column, he wrote, \"The most common clich\u00e9 about the war in Iraq is now this: We didn't have a plan, and now everything is in chaos... This is entirely wrong. We ''did'' have a plan\u2014the problem is that the plan didn't work... We thought a political process inside Iraq would make a military push toward victory against a tripartite foe\u2014Saddamist remnants, foreign terrorists and anti-American Shiites\u2014unnecessary... The only plan that will work is a plan to face the tripartite enemy\u2014the Saddamists, the foreign terrorists and the Shiite sectarians\u2014and bring them to heel. Kill as many bad guys as we can, with as many troops as we can muster.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.nypost.com/seven/12052006/postopinion/opedcolumnists/the_truth_on_iraq_opedcolumnists_john_podhoretz.htm?page=0|title=The Truth on Iraq: Political Answers Won't Work|author=John Podhoretz|newspaper=New York Post|date=December 5, 2006|accessdate=December 20, 2007}} {{Dead link|date=September 2010|bot=H3llBot}}</ref>\n\n====Immigration====\nIn disagreement with several writers at ''National Review'' and conservatives in general, Podhoretz has aggressively favored a more open immigration policy for the United States. He wrote: \"I said merely what I feel deeply\u2014which is that, as a Jew, I have great difficulty supporting a blanket policy of immigration restriction because of what happened to the Jewish people after 1924 and the unwillingness of the United States to take Jews in.\"<ref>{{cite magazine|url=http://corner.nationalreview.com/post/?q=MTM0MjBhMmJjODZiNjIzMDJlZWY5ZWNjYzczM2Q3OWU= |title=Having Been Booed Recently... |date=February 6, 2006 |author=John Podhoretz |magazine=National Review Online |accessdate=September 3, 2006 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071213211236/http://corner.nationalreview.com/post/?q=MTM0MjBhMmJjODZiNjIzMDJlZWY5ZWNjYzczM2Q3OWU%3D |archivedate=December 13, 2007 |df=mdy }}</ref>   Podhoretz was generally supportive of President Bush's proposals for a [[guest worker]] program and a path to [[citizenship]] for certain [[illegal immigrants]] in the U.S.  Yet Podhoretz supports Donald Trump, an admitted racist and classic Jew-hater.\n\nIn November 2007, comments on ''Commentary's'' blog \"Contentions\", Podhoretz attacked his former colleague at ''National Review Online'', [[Mark Krikorian]], for what Podhoretz called a \"vision of a walled-off America primarily under threat from border-crossing immigrants.\" Podhoretz attempted to connect Krikorian's stance on immigration to an [[isolationist]] foreign policy.<ref>{{cite magazine|url=http://www.commentarymagazine.com/blogs/index.php/jpodhoretz/1368 |title=The Anti-Immigration-Isolationism Connection |author=John Podhoretz |date=November 21, 2007 |magazine=Commentary |accessdate=November 25, 2007 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071125125257/http://www.commentarymagazine.com/blogs/index.php/jpodhoretz/1368 |archivedate=November 25, 2007 |df=mdy }}</ref> In response, Krikorian called Podhoretz a \"pedantic bore\" who had no \"actual arguments\" against Krikorian's position on immigration.<ref>{{cite magazine|url=http://corner.nationalreview.com/post/?q=OGUwNjJiNzRmYjcxNzc2MGY3NTk2MDQzZjBmNGU3NDM= |title=Pedantic Bores for $500, Alex |author=Mark Krikorian |date=November 23, 2007 |magazine=National Review Online |accessdate=November 25, 2007 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071124213519/http://corner.nationalreview.com/post/?q=OGUwNjJiNzRmYjcxNzc2MGY3NTk2MDQzZjBmNGU3NDM%3D |archivedate=November 24, 2007 |df=mdy }}</ref>\n\n====Jill Carroll incident====\nOn March 30, 2006, Podhoretz was criticized by various bloggers<ref>{{cite web|url=http://thinkprogress.org/2006/03/30/podhoretz-attacks-carroll/|title=John Podhoretz Attacks Jill Carroll|website=Think Progress|date=March 30, 2006|accessdate=September 3, 2006}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://andrewsullivan.theatlantic.com/the_daily_dish/2006/03/jill_carroll.html|title=Jill Carroll|author=Andrew Sullivan|date=March 30, 2006|publisher=The Daily Dish|accessdate=March 24, 2007}}</ref> for posting the following comment on ''[[National Review Online]]'' approximately three hours after hostage [[Jill Carroll]]'s release from her captors: \"It's wonderful that she's free, but after watching someone who was a hostage for three months say on television she was well-treated because she wasn't beaten or killed\u2014while being dressed in the garb of a modest Muslim woman rather than the non-Muslim woman she actually is\u2014I expect there will be some [[Stockholm syndrome]] talk in the coming days.\"<ref>{{cite magazine|url=http://corner.nationalreview.com/post/?q=Y2I3Y2U4OGIxOTg3ODliNWU3MzQ1MTQ1YzM4YzUzYmE= |title=Jill Carroll |date=March 30, 2006 |author=John Podhoretz |magazine=National Review Online |accessdate=September 3, 2006 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071213210228/http://corner.nationalreview.com/post/?q=Y2I3Y2U4OGIxOTg3ODliNWU3MzQ1MTQ1YzM4YzUzYmE%3D |archivedate=December 13, 2007 |df=mdy }}</ref>\n\nWithin days of Carroll's release, a video of Carroll slamming the \"occupation\" of Iraq and praising the insurgents as \"good people fighting an honorable fight\" appeared on an Islamist website. However, Carroll subsequently released a statement through ''[[The Christian Science Monitor]]'s'' website stating that she participated in the video only because she feared for her life and because her captors said they would let her go if she participated to their satisfaction. Carroll called her captors \"criminals, at best\" and said she remained \"deeply angry\" with them.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.cnn.com/2006/WORLD/meast/04/01/carroll.video/index.html|title=Carroll takes shot at her kidnappers|publisher=CNN.com|date=April 1, 2006|author=Octavia Nasr and Susan Garraty|accessdate=September 3, 2006}}</ref>\n\nOn April 1, 2006, Podhoretz wrote the following on ''National Review Online'': \"For writing these predictive words, which were entirely accurate, I've been pilloried all over the blogosphere. Weird, especially in light of Jill Carroll's statement today, which was an effort to address and quiet precisely the kind of talk I predicted would take place.\"<ref>{{cite magazine|url=http://corner.nationalreview.com/post/?q=NTI1MWY3ZGMzZmJlZDhjYmM5ZDJjNjRlOTM0ZjNkY2Y= |title=Jill Carroll, Continued |author=John Podhoretz |date=April 1, 2007 |magazine=National Review Online |accessdate=September 3, 2006 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071213204817/http://corner.nationalreview.com/post/?q=NTI1MWY3ZGMzZmJlZDhjYmM5ZDJjNjRlOTM0ZjNkY2Y%3D |archivedate=December 13, 2007 |df=mdy }}</ref>\n\n====Conflicts with John Derbyshire====\nIn response to assertions by ''National Review'' writer [[John Derbyshire]] that the victims of the [[Virginia Tech massacre]] should have been more forceful in defending themselves, Podhoretz wrote: \"The notion that a human being or group of human beings holding no weapon whatever should somehow 'fight back' against someone calmly executing other people right in front of their eyes is ludicrous beyond belief, irrational beyond bounds, and tasteless beyond the limits of reason. 'Why didn't anyone rush the guy?' Derb asks. Gee, I don't know. Because he was executing people? Because if you rush a guy with a gun, he shoots you in the head the way he executed the teachers in each classroom?\"<ref>{{cite magazine|url=http://corner.nationalreview.com/post/?q=ZDZkN2NiNjFhNTM4ZGVjMjQyMTE0NjUwOTg1MjU0Yjg= |title=In a Classroom WIth a Gunman |author=John Podhoretz |date=April 19, 2007 |accessdate=April 21, 2007 |magazine=National Review Online |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070422064941/http://corner.nationalreview.com/post/?q=ZDZkN2NiNjFhNTM4ZGVjMjQyMTE0NjUwOTg1MjU0Yjg%3D |archivedate=April 22, 2007 |df=mdy }}</ref> Podhoretz went on to ridicule Derbyshire's claim that he was touching a \"[[Third rail (metaphor)|third rail]]\" by raising a subject nobody else wanted to discuss.{{Citation needed|date=December 2009}}\n\nPodhoretz has frequently clashed with Derbyshire on immigration policy and other issues.\n\n====Other commentary====\nPodhoretz often writes about popular culture, and was called the \"resident pop culture expert\" at ''National Review Online'' by [[Jonah Goldberg]].<ref>{{cite magazine|url=http://corner.nationalreview.com/post/?q=MzhhNWVkOWMzNTliODQ1M2E2MDUxY2Q0OTkwNjdiYWE= |title=Resident Pop Culture Expert |author=Jonah Goldberg |date=September 4, 2006 |magazine=National Review Online |accessdate=March 1, 2007 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071102081319/http://corner.nationalreview.com/post/?q=MzhhNWVkOWMzNTliODQ1M2E2MDUxY2Q0OTkwNjdiYWE%3D |archivedate=November 2, 2007 |df=mdy }}</ref>  [[Dennis Miller]] has called Podhoretz his \"favorite movie reviewer.\"<ref>{{cite interview |last= Miller |first= Dennis |interviewer= Dennis Miller |title= The Dennis Miller Show |last2= Bean |first2= Orson |url= http://www.dennismillerradio.com |date= 2014-05-13 |access-date= January 29, 2020 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20190425013116/http://www.dennismillerradio.com/ |archive-date= April 25, 2019 |url-status= dead }}</ref>  Podhoretz has written that \"it doesn't make sense to judge pop culture by its politics.\"<ref>{{cite magazine|url=http://corner.nationalreview.com/post/?q=MTZiY2FmODEwMzFkMzZiZmRkZGMyYTMyNjFmOTA2ZjA= |title=It Stunk, But It Was Right-Wing |date=October 10, 2006 |author=John Podhoretz |magazine=National Review Online |accessdate=March 1, 2007 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071213211203/http://corner.nationalreview.com/post/?q=MTZiY2FmODEwMzFkMzZiZmRkZGMyYTMyNjFmOTA2ZjA%3D |archivedate=December 13, 2007 |df=mdy }}</ref> In 1999 a column he wrote for ''The New York Post'', \"A Conversation in Hell\",<ref>{{cite web|url=https://nypost.com/1999/07/21/a-conversation-in-hell|work=The New York Post|title=A Conversation in Hell; John Podhoretz|date=July 21, 1999}}</ref> which featured a conversation between [[Satan]] and [[Joseph P. Kennedy, Sr.]], was killed because of its controversial nature.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://nymag.com/nymetro/news/media/features/395/|title=The Devil Made Him Do It|website=NYMag.com}}</ref>\n\n===Personal life and family===\nPodhoretz's first marriage, to Elisabeth Marie Hickey, in 1997,<ref name=nytref1/> ended in divorce after less than three months. Since 2002, he has been married to Ayala Rae Cohen, a former co-producer for ''[[Saturday Night Live]]'', who works for International Creative Management ([[ICM Partners]]).<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.nytimes.com/2002/10/13/style/weddings-celebrations-ayala-cohen-john-podhoretz.html | work=The New York Times | title=WEDDINGS/CELEBRATIONS; Ayala Cohen, John Podhoretz | date=October 13, 2002}}</ref> They have two daughters and a son.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nndb.com/people/426/000048282/|title=John Podhoretz|publisher=NNDB.com|accessdate=April 8, 2007}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.markankcorn.com/?p=114|title=Welcome, Shiri Podhoretz|date=October 23, 2006|publisher=Rabbi Mark Ankcorn|author=Mark Ankcorn|accessdate=April 8, 2006|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070930015822/http://www.markankcorn.com/?p=114|archive-date=September 30, 2007|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite magazine|url=https://www.deadline.com/2012/06/icm-hires-snls-ayala-cohen-for-comedy/|title=ICM Hires SNL's Ayala Cohen For Comedy|first=Nikki|last=Finke|date=June 21, 2012|magazine= Deadline}}</ref> Podhoretz is related by marriage to the diplomat, lawyer and political scientist [[Elliott Abrams]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/ac2/wp-dyn/A41843-2003May26?language=printer|title=Back in Political Forefront|author=Michael Dobbs|date=May 27, 2003|newspaper=The Washington Post|accessdate=October 20, 2007}}</ref>\n\n==Notes==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n==Books==\n{{external media| float = right| video1 = [https://www.c-span.org/video/?53222-1/hell-ride-backstage-white-house ''Booknotes'' interview with Podhoretz on ''Hell of a Ride'', December 19, 1993], [[C-SPAN]]| video2 = [https://www.c-span.org/video/?180855-1/bush-country Presentation by Podhoretz on ''Bush Country'', February 24, 2004], [[C-SPAN]]}} \n* (1993) ''Hell of a Ride: Backstage at the White House Follies 1989\u20131993'', New York: [[Simon & Schuster]], {{ISBN|0-671-79648-8}}\n* (1993) ''A passion for truth: the selected writings of Eric Breindel'', New York: [[HarperCollins Publishers]], editor {{ISBN|0-671-79648-8}}\n* (2004) ''Bush Country: How Dubya Became a Great President While Driving Liberals Insane'', New York: [[St. Martin's Press]], {{ISBN|0-312-32473-1}}\n* (2007) ''Can She Be Stopped?: Hillary Clinton Will Be the Next President of the United States Unless...'', New York: [[Crown Forum]], {{ISBN|0-307-33730-8}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20050922232245/http://corner.nationalreview.com/ The Corner] at ''National Review Online''\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20060529210533/http://www.newyorkmetro.com/nymetro/news/media/features/1968/ \"Oedipus and Podhoretz\"], an article from ''[[New York (magazine)|New York]]'' by [[Hanna Rosin]]\n* {{C-SPAN|johnpodhoretz}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Podhoretz, John}}\n[[Category:American political writers]]\n[[Category:American male non-fiction writers]]\n[[Category:American speechwriters]]\n[[Category:American columnists]]\n[[Category:Jewish American writers]]\n[[Category:Jeopardy! contestants]]\n[[Category:1961 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:University of Chicago alumni]]\n[[Category:The Weekly Standard people]]\n[[Category:The American Spectator people]]\n[[Category:Reagan administration personnel]]\n[[Category:New York (state) Republicans]]\n[[Category:The Washington Times people]]\n[[Category:People from the Upper West Side]]\n[[Category:Columbia Grammar & Preparatory School alumni]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American writer|bot=PearBOT 5}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=June 2013}}\n{{Infobox person\n | image            =\n | name             = John Podhoretz\n | birth_name       = John Mordecai Podhoretz\n | birth_date       = {{birth date and age|1961|4|18}}\n | birth_place      = [[New York City]], New York, U.S.\n | death_date       =\n | death_place      =\n | education        = [[University of Chicago]]\n | occupation       = Author, columnist, [[Pundit (expert)|pundit]], film critic\n | alma_mater       =\n | alias            =\n | title            =\n | family           =\n | spouse           = {{marriage|Elisabeth Marie Hickey|1996|end=divorced}}<br>{{marriage|Ayala Rae Cohen|2002}}\n | children         =\n | relatives        =\n | salary           =\n | networth         =\n | credits          =\n | agent            =\n | URL              =\n}}\n\n'''John Mordecai Podhoretz'''<ref name=nytref1>{{cite news| url=https://www.nytimes.com/1997/05/25/style/elisabeth-hickey-john-podhoretz.html | work=The New York Times | title=Elisabeth Hickey, John Podhoretz | date=May 25, 1997}}</ref> ({{IPAc-en|p|\u0252|d|\u02c8|h|\u0252r|\u025b|t|s}}; born April 18, 1961) is an American writer. He is the editor of ''[[Commentary (magazine)|Commentary]]'' magazine, a columnist for the ''[[New York Post]]'', the author of several books on politics, and a former [[speechwriter]] for [[President of the United States|Presidents]] [[Ronald Reagan]] and [[George H. W. Bush]].\n\n==Life and career==\nPodhoretz was born to a [[American Jews|Jewish]] family in New York City, the son of conservative journalists [[Norman Podhoretz]] and [[Midge Decter]]; he is his mother's youngest child of four, and his father's youngest child of two. He grew up on the [[Upper West Side]] in New York City. He attended [[Columbia Grammar and Preparatory School]] and he received a bachelor's degree from the [[University of Chicago]] in 1982. In 1986, he became a five-time champion on the game show ''[[Jeopardy!]]''.\n\nPodhoretz served as [[speechwriter]] to former U.S. President [[Ronald Reagan]] as well as former President [[George H.W. Bush]]. He also served in the capacity of special assistant to White House [[Drug Czar]] [[William Bennett]]. He was co-founder as well of the [[White House Writers Group]], a corporate speechwriting and public-relations firm in Washington, D.C.<ref name=autogenerated1>{{cite web|url=http://www.greatertalent.com/speakers/speakers.php?speakerid=432 |title=John Podhoretz |publisher=Greater Talent Network |accessdate=April 8, 2007 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20061029031306/http://www.greatertalent.com/speakers/speakers.php?speakerid=432 |archivedate=October 29, 2006 }}</ref>\n\nPodhoretz was a consultant for the popular television series ''[[The West Wing]]'', including the controversial episode \"[[Gaza (The West Wing)|Gaza]]\" in season five, first broadcast on May 12, 2004.<ref>{{IMDb name|id=1885020|name=John Podhoretz|accessdate=April 8, 2007}}</ref>\n\nPodhoretz has contributed to a number of conservative publications, including ''[[National Review]]'' and the ''[[Weekly Standard]]'', where he is a movie critic and was the magazine's deputy editor. He was also a consulting editor at [[ReganBooks]], a former imprint of [[HarperCollins]]. Podhoretz has a regular column at the ''[[New York Post]]''. He has also appeared on television as a political commentator, on [[Fox News]], [[CNN]]'s ''Reliable Sources'', MSNBC, and ''[[The McLaughlin Group]]'' (in the chair usually occupied by conservative [[Tony Blankley]]), among other places. He has also worked at ''[[Time magazine|Time]]'', the ''[[Washington Times]]'', ''[[Insight on the News]]'', and ''[[U.S. News & World Report]]''. Podhoretz was a contributor to The Corner, a group blog run by ''National Review''.\n\nAt ''[[The Weekly Standard]]'', one staff member said, Podhoretz's \"arrogance and egotism had a psychological effect people can't quite believe.\" At ''[[The Washington Times]]'' a colleague reported, he was \"permanently frozen in juvenalia.\" Glenn Garvin, the Central American bureau chief of the ''Miami Herald'', once said that at the ''Times'', Podhoretz \"constantly complained that his brilliance wasn't appreciated.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://nymag.com/nymetro/news/media/features/1968/index1.html|title=Oedipus & Podhoretz|website=NYMag.com}}</ref>\n\nOn January 1, 2009, Podhoretz became editor of ''[[Commentary (magazine)|Commentary]]'', succeeding [[Neal Kozodoy]], who had been editor since 1995, when Norman Podhoretz retired. Kozodoy is currently Editor-at-Large.\n\n===Political commentary===\n\n====George W. Bush====\nPodhoretz was a steadfast supporter of U.S. president [[George W. Bush]], and his 2004 book ''Bush Country'' called Bush \"the first great leader of the 21st century\". When some conservatives denounced Bush's immigration plan, Podhoretz wrote that Bush's \"efforts on behalf of conservative causes\u2014from faith-based policies to stem-cell research to a strict-constructionist judiciary to entitlement reform and massive tax cuts\u2014have all fallen down the memory hole\".<ref>{{cite magazine|url=http://corner.nationalreview.com/post/?q=NGJkMWM2MmExZDZkYTI2MmFmNTZiODQ3MjNjNmQwYzA= |title=The Inability to Stomach Disagreement |magazine=National Review Online |author=John Podhoretz |date=May 16, 2006 |accessdate=September 3, 2006 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20060806092940/http://corner.nationalreview.com/post/?q=NGJkMWM2MmExZDZkYTI2MmFmNTZiODQ3MjNjNmQwYzA%3D |archivedate=August 6, 2006 |df=mdy }}</ref>\n\n====Israel====\nPodhoretz is emphatic in his defense of [[Israel]] in its conflicts with its [[Arab]] neighbors. When pundit [[Pat Buchanan]] called Israel's actions in the [[2006 Lebanon War]] \"un-Christian\", Podhoretz wrote: \"You want to know what [[anti-Semitism]] is? When Pat Buchanan calls Israel's military action 'un-Christian.' That's anti-Semitism.\"<ref>{{cite magazine|url=http://corner.nationalreview.com/post/?q=ZjU4OTZkMDUzYWJjNGYwNmVmYTFkNDlmYmY1NjY5ZGE= |title=You Want to Know What Anti-Semitism Is? |date=July 21, 2006 |author=John Podhoretz |magazine=National Review Online |accessdate=September 3, 2006 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20060822103825/http://corner.nationalreview.com/post/?q=ZjU4OTZkMDUzYWJjNGYwNmVmYTFkNDlmYmY1NjY5ZGE%3D |archivedate=August 22, 2006 |df=mdy }}</ref>\n\n====Iraq War====\nPodhoretz has supported the [[Iraq War]] from its inception until the present. In his book, ''Bush Country'', he wrote, \"The natural terrorist hunger to acquire WMDs, and Saddam Hussein's desire to humiliate the United States, combined to make Iraq a new kind of threat to America and the world.\" In a July 25, 2006 column for the ''New York Post'' that discussed the Israel-Lebanon conflict, Podhoretz advocated a more Machiavellian policy in Iraq, writing: \"What if the tactical mistake we made in Iraq was that we didn't kill enough Sunnis in the early going to intimidate them and make them so afraid of us they would go along with anything? Wasn't the survival of Sunni men between the ages of 15 and 35 the reason there was an insurgency and the basic cause of the sectarian violence now?\"<ref>{{cite news|url=http://pqarchiver.nypost.com/nypost/access/1083003321.html?dids=1083003321:1083003321&FMT=ABS&FMTS=ABS:FT&date=Jul+25%2C+2006&author=John+Podhoretz&pub=New+York+Post&edition=&startpage=029&desc=TOO+NICE+TO+WIN%3F+ISRAEL%27S+DILEMMA |archive-url=https://archive.is/20120715210444/http://pqarchiver.nypost.com/nypost/access/1083003321.html?dids=1083003321:1083003321&FMT=ABS&FMTS=ABS:FT&date=Jul+25,+2006&author=John+Podhoretz&pub=New+York+Post&edition=&startpage=029&desc=TOO+NICE+TO+WIN%3F+ISRAEL'S+DILEMMA |url-status=dead |archive-date=July 15, 2012 |title=Too Nice to Win? Israel's Dilemma |author=John Podhoretz |newspaper=New York Post |date=July 25, 2006 |accessdate=April 7, 2007 }}</ref> In a December 2006 column, he wrote, \"The most common clich\u00e9 about the war in Iraq is now this: We didn't have a plan, and now everything is in chaos... This is entirely wrong. We ''did'' have a plan\u2014the problem is that the plan didn't work... We thought a political process inside Iraq would make a military push toward victory against a tripartite foe\u2014Saddamist remnants, foreign terrorists and anti-American Shiites\u2014unnecessary... The only plan that will work is a plan to face the tripartite enemy\u2014the Saddamists, the foreign terrorists and the Shiite sectarians\u2014and bring them to heel. Kill as many bad guys as we can, with as many troops as we can muster.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.nypost.com/seven/12052006/postopinion/opedcolumnists/the_truth_on_iraq_opedcolumnists_john_podhoretz.htm?page=0|title=The Truth on Iraq: Political Answers Won't Work|author=John Podhoretz|newspaper=New York Post|date=December 5, 2006|accessdate=December 20, 2007}} {{Dead link|date=September 2010|bot=H3llBot}}</ref>\n\n====Immigration====\nIn disagreement with several writers at ''National Review'' and conservatives in general, Podhoretz has aggressively favored a more open immigration policy for the United States. He wrote: \"I said merely what I feel deeply\u2014which is that, as a Jew, I have great difficulty supporting a blanket policy of immigration restriction because of what happened to the Jewish people after 1924 and the unwillingness of the United States to take Jews in.\"<ref>{{cite magazine|url=http://corner.nationalreview.com/post/?q=MTM0MjBhMmJjODZiNjIzMDJlZWY5ZWNjYzczM2Q3OWU= |title=Having Been Booed Recently... |date=February 6, 2006 |author=John Podhoretz |magazine=National Review Online |accessdate=September 3, 2006 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071213211236/http://corner.nationalreview.com/post/?q=MTM0MjBhMmJjODZiNjIzMDJlZWY5ZWNjYzczM2Q3OWU%3D |archivedate=December 13, 2007 |df=mdy }}</ref>   Podhoretz was generally supportive of President Bush's proposals for a [[guest worker]] program and a path to [[citizenship]] for certain [[illegal immigrants]] in the U.S.\n\nIn November 2007, comments on ''Commentary's'' blog \"Contentions\", Podhoretz attacked his former colleague at ''National Review Online'', [[Mark Krikorian]], for what Podhoretz called a \"vision of a walled-off America primarily under threat from border-crossing immigrants.\" Podhoretz attempted to connect Krikorian's stance on immigration to an [[isolationist]] foreign policy.<ref>{{cite magazine|url=http://www.commentarymagazine.com/blogs/index.php/jpodhoretz/1368 |title=The Anti-Immigration-Isolationism Connection |author=John Podhoretz |date=November 21, 2007 |magazine=Commentary |accessdate=November 25, 2007 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071125125257/http://www.commentarymagazine.com/blogs/index.php/jpodhoretz/1368 |archivedate=November 25, 2007 |df=mdy }}</ref> In response, Krikorian called Podhoretz a \"pedantic bore\" who had no \"actual arguments\" against Krikorian's position on immigration.<ref>{{cite magazine|url=http://corner.nationalreview.com/post/?q=OGUwNjJiNzRmYjcxNzc2MGY3NTk2MDQzZjBmNGU3NDM= |title=Pedantic Bores for $500, Alex |author=Mark Krikorian |date=November 23, 2007 |magazine=National Review Online |accessdate=November 25, 2007 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071124213519/http://corner.nationalreview.com/post/?q=OGUwNjJiNzRmYjcxNzc2MGY3NTk2MDQzZjBmNGU3NDM%3D |archivedate=November 24, 2007 |df=mdy }}</ref>\n\n====Jill Carroll incident====\nOn March 30, 2006, Podhoretz was criticized by various bloggers<ref>{{cite web|url=http://thinkprogress.org/2006/03/30/podhoretz-attacks-carroll/|title=John Podhoretz Attacks Jill Carroll|website=Think Progress|date=March 30, 2006|accessdate=September 3, 2006}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://andrewsullivan.theatlantic.com/the_daily_dish/2006/03/jill_carroll.html|title=Jill Carroll|author=Andrew Sullivan|date=March 30, 2006|publisher=The Daily Dish|accessdate=March 24, 2007}}</ref> for posting the following comment on ''[[National Review Online]]'' approximately three hours after hostage [[Jill Carroll]]'s release from her captors: \"It's wonderful that she's free, but after watching someone who was a hostage for three months say on television she was well-treated because she wasn't beaten or killed\u2014while being dressed in the garb of a modest Muslim woman rather than the non-Muslim woman she actually is\u2014I expect there will be some [[Stockholm syndrome]] talk in the coming days.\"<ref>{{cite magazine|url=http://corner.nationalreview.com/post/?q=Y2I3Y2U4OGIxOTg3ODliNWU3MzQ1MTQ1YzM4YzUzYmE= |title=Jill Carroll |date=March 30, 2006 |author=John Podhoretz |magazine=National Review Online |accessdate=September 3, 2006 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071213210228/http://corner.nationalreview.com/post/?q=Y2I3Y2U4OGIxOTg3ODliNWU3MzQ1MTQ1YzM4YzUzYmE%3D |archivedate=December 13, 2007 |df=mdy }}</ref>\n\nWithin days of Carroll's release, a video of Carroll slamming the \"occupation\" of Iraq and praising the insurgents as \"good people fighting an honorable fight\" appeared on an Islamist website. However, Carroll subsequently released a statement through ''[[The Christian Science Monitor]]'s'' website stating that she participated in the video only because she feared for her life and because her captors said they would let her go if she participated to their satisfaction. Carroll called her captors \"criminals, at best\" and said she remained \"deeply angry\" with them.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.cnn.com/2006/WORLD/meast/04/01/carroll.video/index.html|title=Carroll takes shot at her kidnappers|publisher=CNN.com|date=April 1, 2006|author=Octavia Nasr and Susan Garraty|accessdate=September 3, 2006}}</ref>\n\nOn April 1, 2006, Podhoretz wrote the following on ''National Review Online'': \"For writing these predictive words, which were entirely accurate, I've been pilloried all over the blogosphere. Weird, especially in light of Jill Carroll's statement today, which was an effort to address and quiet precisely the kind of talk I predicted would take place.\"<ref>{{cite magazine|url=http://corner.nationalreview.com/post/?q=NTI1MWY3ZGMzZmJlZDhjYmM5ZDJjNjRlOTM0ZjNkY2Y= |title=Jill Carroll, Continued |author=John Podhoretz |date=April 1, 2007 |magazine=National Review Online |accessdate=September 3, 2006 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071213204817/http://corner.nationalreview.com/post/?q=NTI1MWY3ZGMzZmJlZDhjYmM5ZDJjNjRlOTM0ZjNkY2Y%3D |archivedate=December 13, 2007 |df=mdy }}</ref>\n\n====Conflicts with John Derbyshire====\nIn response to assertions by ''National Review'' writer [[John Derbyshire]] that the victims of the [[Virginia Tech massacre]] should have been more forceful in defending themselves, Podhoretz wrote: \"The notion that a human being or group of human beings holding no weapon whatever should somehow 'fight back' against someone calmly executing other people right in front of their eyes is ludicrous beyond belief, irrational beyond bounds, and tasteless beyond the limits of reason. 'Why didn't anyone rush the guy?' Derb asks. Gee, I don't know. Because he was executing people? Because if you rush a guy with a gun, he shoots you in the head the way he executed the teachers in each classroom?\"<ref>{{cite magazine|url=http://corner.nationalreview.com/post/?q=ZDZkN2NiNjFhNTM4ZGVjMjQyMTE0NjUwOTg1MjU0Yjg= |title=In a Classroom WIth a Gunman |author=John Podhoretz |date=April 19, 2007 |accessdate=April 21, 2007 |magazine=National Review Online |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070422064941/http://corner.nationalreview.com/post/?q=ZDZkN2NiNjFhNTM4ZGVjMjQyMTE0NjUwOTg1MjU0Yjg%3D |archivedate=April 22, 2007 |df=mdy }}</ref> Podhoretz went on to ridicule Derbyshire's claim that he was touching a \"[[Third rail (metaphor)|third rail]]\" by raising a subject nobody else wanted to discuss.{{Citation needed|date=December 2009}}\n\nPodhoretz has frequently clashed with Derbyshire on immigration policy and other issues.\n\n====Other commentary====\nPodhoretz often writes about popular culture, and was called the \"resident pop culture expert\" at ''National Review Online'' by [[Jonah Goldberg]].<ref>{{cite magazine|url=http://corner.nationalreview.com/post/?q=MzhhNWVkOWMzNTliODQ1M2E2MDUxY2Q0OTkwNjdiYWE= |title=Resident Pop Culture Expert |author=Jonah Goldberg |date=September 4, 2006 |magazine=National Review Online |accessdate=March 1, 2007 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071102081319/http://corner.nationalreview.com/post/?q=MzhhNWVkOWMzNTliODQ1M2E2MDUxY2Q0OTkwNjdiYWE%3D |archivedate=November 2, 2007 |df=mdy }}</ref>  [[Dennis Miller]] has called Podhoretz his \"favorite movie reviewer.\"<ref>{{cite interview |last= Miller |first= Dennis |interviewer= Dennis Miller |title= The Dennis Miller Show |last2= Bean |first2= Orson |url= http://www.dennismillerradio.com |date= 2014-05-13 |access-date= January 29, 2020 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20190425013116/http://www.dennismillerradio.com/ |archive-date= April 25, 2019 |url-status= dead }}</ref>  Podhoretz has written that \"it doesn't make sense to judge pop culture by its politics.\"<ref>{{cite magazine|url=http://corner.nationalreview.com/post/?q=MTZiY2FmODEwMzFkMzZiZmRkZGMyYTMyNjFmOTA2ZjA= |title=It Stunk, But It Was Right-Wing |date=October 10, 2006 |author=John Podhoretz |magazine=National Review Online |accessdate=March 1, 2007 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071213211203/http://corner.nationalreview.com/post/?q=MTZiY2FmODEwMzFkMzZiZmRkZGMyYTMyNjFmOTA2ZjA%3D |archivedate=December 13, 2007 |df=mdy }}</ref> In 1999 a column he wrote for ''The New York Post'', \"A Conversation in Hell\",<ref>{{cite web|url=https://nypost.com/1999/07/21/a-conversation-in-hell|work=The New York Post|title=A Conversation in Hell; John Podhoretz|date=July 21, 1999}}</ref> which featured a conversation between [[Satan]] and [[Joseph P. Kennedy, Sr.]], was killed because of its controversial nature.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://nymag.com/nymetro/news/media/features/395/|title=The Devil Made Him Do It|website=NYMag.com}}</ref>\n\n===Personal life and family===\nPodhoretz's first marriage, to Elisabeth Marie Hickey, in 1997,<ref name=nytref1/> ended in divorce after less than three months. Since 2002, he has been married to Ayala Rae Cohen, a former co-producer for ''[[Saturday Night Live]]'', who works for International Creative Management ([[ICM Partners]]).<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.nytimes.com/2002/10/13/style/weddings-celebrations-ayala-cohen-john-podhoretz.html | work=The New York Times | title=WEDDINGS/CELEBRATIONS; Ayala Cohen, John Podhoretz | date=October 13, 2002}}</ref> They have two daughters and a son.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nndb.com/people/426/000048282/|title=John Podhoretz|publisher=NNDB.com|accessdate=April 8, 2007}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.markankcorn.com/?p=114|title=Welcome, Shiri Podhoretz|date=October 23, 2006|publisher=Rabbi Mark Ankcorn|author=Mark Ankcorn|accessdate=April 8, 2006|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070930015822/http://www.markankcorn.com/?p=114|archive-date=September 30, 2007|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite magazine|url=https://www.deadline.com/2012/06/icm-hires-snls-ayala-cohen-for-comedy/|title=ICM Hires SNL's Ayala Cohen For Comedy|first=Nikki|last=Finke|date=June 21, 2012|magazine= Deadline}}</ref> Podhoretz is related by marriage to the diplomat, lawyer and political scientist [[Elliott Abrams]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/ac2/wp-dyn/A41843-2003May26?language=printer|title=Back in Political Forefront|author=Michael Dobbs|date=May 27, 2003|newspaper=The Washington Post|accessdate=October 20, 2007}}</ref>\n\n==Notes==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n==Books==\n{{external media| float = right| video1 = [https://www.c-span.org/video/?53222-1/hell-ride-backstage-white-house ''Booknotes'' interview with Podhoretz on ''Hell of a Ride'', December 19, 1993], [[C-SPAN]]| video2 = [https://www.c-span.org/video/?180855-1/bush-country Presentation by Podhoretz on ''Bush Country'', February 24, 2004], [[C-SPAN]]}} \n* (1993) ''Hell of a Ride: Backstage at the White House Follies 1989\u20131993'', New York: [[Simon & Schuster]], {{ISBN|0-671-79648-8}}\n* (1993) ''A passion for truth: the selected writings of Eric Breindel'', New York: [[HarperCollins Publishers]], editor {{ISBN|0-671-79648-8}}\n* (2004) ''Bush Country: How Dubya Became a Great President While Driving Liberals Insane'', New York: [[St. Martin's Press]], {{ISBN|0-312-32473-1}}\n* (2007) ''Can She Be Stopped?: Hillary Clinton Will Be the Next President of the United States Unless...'', New York: [[Crown Forum]], {{ISBN|0-307-33730-8}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20050922232245/http://corner.nationalreview.com/ The Corner] at ''National Review Online''\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20060529210533/http://www.newyorkmetro.com/nymetro/news/media/features/1968/ \"Oedipus and Podhoretz\"], an article from ''[[New York (magazine)|New York]]'' by [[Hanna Rosin]]\n* {{C-SPAN|johnpodhoretz}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Podhoretz, John}}\n[[Category:American political writers]]\n[[Category:American male non-fiction writers]]\n[[Category:American speechwriters]]\n[[Category:American columnists]]\n[[Category:Jewish American writers]]\n[[Category:Jeopardy! contestants]]\n[[Category:1961 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:University of Chicago alumni]]\n[[Category:The Weekly Standard people]]\n[[Category:The American Spectator people]]\n[[Category:Reagan administration personnel]]\n[[Category:New York (state) Republicans]]\n[[Category:The Washington Times people]]\n[[Category:People from the Upper West Side]]\n[[Category:Columbia Grammar & Preparatory School alumni]]\n", "name_user": "100.12.173.161", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(\u2192\u200eImmigration)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/John_Podhoretz"}
{"title_page": "List of revolutions and rebellions", "text_new": "{{short description|Wikimedia list article}}\n{{see also|List of coups d'\u00e9tat and coup attempts|List of invasions}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n[[File:Prise de la Bastille.jpg|thumb|right|250px|The [[storming of the Bastille]], 14 July 1789, during the [[French Revolution]].]]\n[[File:Vereshchagin-Blowing from Guns in British India.jpg|thumb|right|250px|''[[Suppression of the Indian Revolt by the English]]'', which depicts the execution of mutineers by blowing from a gun by the British, a painting by [[Vasily Vereshchagin]] {{lang|la|{{abbr|c.|circa}}}} 1884. Note: This painting was allegedly bought by the British crown and possibly destroyed (current whereabouts unknown). It anachronistically depicts [[Indian Rebellion of 1857|the events of 1857]] with soldiers wearing (then current) uniforms of the late 19th century.]]\n\nThis is a '''list of [[revolutions]] and [[rebellion]]s'''.\n<!-- It is not meant to include every instance of violent conflict. Do not add battles and wars which are unconnected to a revolution or rebellion. Do not add \"revolutions\" mandated from above. Do not add every riot and violent demonstration in the history of mankind, and do not accord recent events undue weight. Note: there is a section at the end, \"Cultural, intellectual, philosophical and technological revolutions\", which does list some significant events, phenomena or trends which are not violent rebellions or revolutions.  That may be split off later.-->\n{{Expand list|date=November 2019}}\n\n==BC==\n:{{legend2|#AF9|style=\"background:#AF9\"|Revolutionary/rebel victory|border=1px solid #AAA}}\n:{{legend2|#F88|style=\"background:#F88\"|Revolutionary/rebel defeat|border=1px solid #AAA}}\n:{{legend2|#BBF|Another result (e.g. a treaty or peace without a clear result, ''status quo ante bellum'', result unknown or indecisive)|border=1px solid #AAA}}\n:{{legend2||Ongoing conflict|border=1px solid #AAA}}\n\n