led|publisher=Eisenbrauns|year=2005|isbn=978-1575060958|location=|pages=|ref=CITEREFLipschits2005|page=13-18}}</ref>\n|-\n|570 BC\n|[[Amasis II|Amasis]] revolt\n|[[File:Double_crown.svg|20px]] [[Twenty-sixth Dynasty of Egypt|Egypt]]\n|[[Egyptians|Egyptian]] soldiers\n|style=\"background:#AF9\"|Pharoah [[Apries]] was overthrown and exiled, giving [[Amasis II]] the opportunity to seize the throne. Apries later attempted to retake Egypt, with Babylonian support, but was defeated and killed.\n|[[File:Median_Empire-en.svg|100px]]\n|<ref name=\"Clayton 195-97\">{{cite book |last=Clayton |first=Peter A. |title=Chronicle of the Pharaohs: The Reign-by-Reign Record of the Rulers and Dynasties of Ancient Egypt |publisher=Thames &amp; Hudson |edition=Paperback |pages=195\u2013197 |year=2006 |isbn=0-500-28628-0 }}</ref>\n|-\n|552\u2013550 BC\n|[[Persian Revolt]]\n|[[Persis]], [[Media (region)|Media]]\n|[[Persians]], led by [[Cyrus the Great]]\n|style=\"background:#AF9\"|Median rule overthrown, Persis and Media become part of the new [[Achaemenid Empire]]\n|[[File:Jean_Charles_Nicaise_Perrin_-_Cyrus_and_Astyages_-_WGA17209.jpg|100px]]\n|\n|-\n|522 BC\n|[[Darius the Great#Early reign|Anti-Achaemeneid Rebellions]]\n|[[File:Standard_of_Cyrus_the_Great_(White).svg|20px]] [[Achaemenid Empire]]\n|[[Assyria]]ns, [[Babylonians]], [[Egyptians]], [[Elamites]], [[Medians]] and [[Parthian Empire|Parthians]]\n|style=\"background:#F88\"|[[Darius the Great]] quashes all the rebellions within the space of a year.\n|[[File:Gaumata_being_trampled_upon_by_Darius.jpg|100px]]\n|<ref>{{cite book | title = From Cyrus to Alexander: A History of the Persian Empire | year = 2002 | publisher = Eisenbrauns | last = Briant | first = Pierre | isbn = 9781575061207 | url = https://books.google.dk/books?id=lxQ9W6F1oSYC&dq=false |ref=|pages=115-116}}</ref>\n|-\n|510\u2013509 BC\n|[[Overthrow of the Roman monarchy|Roman Revolution]]\n|[[File:Capitoline_Wolf_of_Roman_Kingdom.svg|20px]] [[Roman Kingdom|Rome]]\n|[[Roman Republic|Republicans]]\n|style=\"background:#AF9\"|The [[Overthrow of the Roman monarchy|Roman monarchy was overthrown]] and in its place the [[Roman Republic]] was established.\n|[[File:Suicide_lucretia.jpg|100px]]\n|<ref name=\"ReferenceC\">[[Livy]], ''[[Ab urbe condita (book)|Ab urbe condita]]'', [http://www.gutenberg.org/files/19725/19725-h/19725-h.htm#a57 1.57]</ref>\n|-\n|508\u2013507 BC\n|[[Athenian Revolution]]\n|[[File:Owl_of_Minerva.png|20px]] [[Classical Athens|Athens]]\n|[[Athenian Democracy|Democrats]]\n|style=\"background:#AF9\"|The [[Tyrant]] [[Hippias (tyrant)|Hippias]] was deposed and the subequent [[aristocratic]] [[oligarchy]] overthrown, establishing [[Athenian Democracy|Democracy]] in [[Classical Athens|Athens]].\n|[[File:Ceremony_of_Presenting_Earth_and_Water.jpg|100px]]\n|<ref name=\"Ober1996\">{{cite book |title=The Athenian Revolution|last=Ober|first=Josiah|authorlink=Josiah Ober|year=1996|pages=32\u201352|publisher=Princeton University Press|isbn=}}</ref>\n|-\n|499\u2013493 BC\n|[[Ionian Revolt]]\n|[[Ionia]], [[File:Standard_of_Cyrus_the_Great_(White).svg|20px]] [[Achaemenid Empire]]\n|[[Greeks]]\n|style=\"background:#F88\"|The [[Achaemenid Empire]] asserts its rule over the [[city states]] of [[Ionia]].\n|[[File:Ionian_Revolt_Campaign_Map-en.svg|100px]]\n|<ref name = VI33>Herodotus [http://www.perseus.tufts.edu/cgi-bin/ptext?doc=Perseus%3Atext%3A1999.01.0126&layout=&loc=6.33 VI, 33]</ref>\n|-\n|494 BC\n|[[First secessio plebis]]\n|[[File:Roman_SPQR_banner.svg|20px]] [[Roman Republic]]\n|[[Plebs|Plebeians]]\n|style=\"background:#AF9\"|[[Patricians]] freed some of the plebs from their debts and conceded some of their power by creating the office of the [[Tribune of the Plebs]].\n|[[File:Secessio_plebis.JPG|100px]]\n|<ref>[[Livy]], ''[[Ab urbe condita (book)|Ab urbe condita]]'', Book 2</ref>\n|-\n|484 BC\n|[[Bel-shimanni]]'s rebellion\n|[[Babylon]], [[File:Standard_of_Cyrus_the_Great_(White).svg|20px]] [[Achaemenid Empire]]\n|[[Babylonians]]\n|style=\"background:#F88\"|Rebellion quickly defeated by [[Xerxes I]]. \n|\n|<ref name=\"Esagila\">{{Cite journal|last=Dandamaev|first=Muhammad A.|date=1993|title=Xerxes and the Esagila Temple in Babylon|journal=Bulletin of the Asia Institute|volume=7|pages=41\u201345|ref=CITEREFDandamaev1993|jstor=24048423}}</ref>\n|-\n|482\u2013481 BC\n|[[Shamash-eriba]]'s rebellion\n|[[Babylon]], [[File:Standard_of_Cyrus_the_Great_(White).svg|20px]] [[Achaemenid Empire]]\n|[[Babylonians]]\n|style=\"background:#F88\"|Rebellion eventually defeated by [[Xerxes I]], Babylon's forticiations were destroyed and its temples were ransacked. \n|\n|<ref name=\"Esagila\"/>\n|-\n|464 BC\n|[[Third Messenian War]]\n|[[File:Sparta_shield.svg|20px]] [[Sparta]]\n|[[Messenian]] [[Helots]]\n|style=\"background:#F88\"|Slave revolt put down by [[Archidamus II]], who called Sparta to arms in the wake of an [[464 BC Sparta earthquake|earthquake]].\n|\n|<ref name=\"EB1911\">{{EB1911|inline=y|wstitle=Archidamus|display=Archidamus s.v. 2|volume=2|page=367|first=Marcus Niebuhr|last=Tod}}</ref>\n|-\n|460\u2013454 BC\n|[[Inaros II|Inaros]]' revolt\n|[[Twenty-seventh Dynasty of Egypt|Egypt]], [[File:Standard_of_Cyrus_the_Great_(White).svg|20px]] [[Achaemenid Empire]]\n|[[Inaros II]] and his [[Classical Athens|Athenian]] allies\n|style=\"background:#F88\"|Defeated by the Persian army led by [[Megabyzus]] and [[Artabazus]], after a two-year siege. Inaros was captured and carried away to [[Susa]] where he was [[crucified]]. \n|[[File:Wars_of_the_Delian_League_Egyptian_campaign.jpg|100px]]\n|<ref>Herodotus [http://www.perseus.tufts.edu/cgi-bin/ptext?doc=Perseus%3Atext%3A1999.01.0126;query=chapter%3D%231435;layout=;loc=8.127.1 VIII, 126]</ref><ref name = DSXI77>Diodorus [http://www.perseus.tufts.edu/cgi-bin/ptext?doc=Perseus%3Atext%3A1999.01.0084;query=chapter%3D%23153;layout=;loc=11.76.1 XI, 77]</ref>\n|-\n|449 BC\n|[[Secessio plebis#Second Secession \u2013 449 BC|Second Secessio plebis]]\n|[[File:Roman_SPQR_banner.svg|20px]] [[Roman Republic]]\n|[[Plebs|Plebeians]]\n|style=\"background:#AF9\"|The [[Roman Senate|Senate]] forced the resignation of the [[Decemviri]] and restored both the office of [[Tribune of the Plebs]] and the right of appeal, which were suspended during the rule of the Decemvir. \n|[[File:Seven_Hills_of_Rome.svg|100px]]\n|<ref>[[Livy]], ''[[Ab urbe condita]]'' 3.55.13 </ref><ref>{{cite book|last=Cornell|first=T.J.|title=\"The Beginnings of Rome\"|publisher=Routledge|date=1995|page=265}}</ref>\n|-\n|445 BC\n|[[Secessio plebis#Third Secession \u2013 445 BC|Third Secessio plebis]]\n|[[File:Roman_SPQR_banner.svg|20px]] [[Roman Republic]]\n|[[Plebs|Plebeians]]\n|style=\"background:#AF9\"|Intermarriage between [[Patricians]] and [[Plebeians]] was legalized and the position of [[Tribuni militum consulari potestate|Consular Tribune]] (a [[Tribune of the Plebs]] elected with the powers of a [[Roman Consul|consul]]) was created.\n|\n|<ref name=\"Livy iv 6-7\">{{cite book|last=[[Livy]]|title=''[[Ab urbe condita]]''|chapter=6-7}}</ref><ref>Dionysius, xi. 60.}}</ref>\n|-\n|342 BC\n|[[Secessio plebis#Fourth Secession \u2013 342 BC|Fourth Secessio plebis]]\n|[[File:Roman_SPQR_banner.svg|20px]] [[Roman Republic]]\n|[[Plebs|Plebeians]]\n|style=\"background:#BBF\"|\n|\n|<ref name=\"Livy iv 6-7\"/>\n|-\n|287 BC\n|[[Secessio plebis#Fifth Secession \u2013 287 BC|Fifth Secessio plebis]]\n|[[File:Roman_SPQR_banner.svg|20px]] [[Roman Republic]]\n|[[Plebs|Plebeians]]\n|style=\"background:#AF9\"|The ''[[Lex Hortensia]]'' was implemented, establishing that the laws decided by the [[Plebeian Council]] were made binding on all Roman citizens, including [[patricians]]. This law finally eliminated the political disparity between the two classes, bringing the [[Conflict of Orders]] to an end after about two hundred years of struggle.\n|\n|<ref>{{cite book|last=[[Works attributed to Florus|Floro]]|title=Epitome of Roman History|chapter=X}}</ref>\n|-\n|241 BC\n|Revolt of the [[Falisci]]\n|[[File:Roman_SPQR_banner.svg|20px]] [[Roman Republic]]\n|[[Falisci]]\n|style=\"background:#F88\"|The Falisci were defeated and subjugated to Roman dominance, the town of [[Falerii]] was destroyed.\n|[[File:Iron_Age_Italy.png|100px]]\n|<ref> Zonaras: 8, in Cassius Dio, Roman History, Fragments of Book 12 [http://penelope.uchicago.edu/Thayer/E/Roman/Texts/Cassius_Dio/12*.html]</ref>\n|-\n|209 BC\n|[[Dazexiang uprising]]\n|[[Qin dynasty|China]]\n|[[Villagers]]{{dn|date=April 2020}} led by [[Chen Sheng]] and [[Wu Guang]]\n|style=\"background:#F88\"|The uprising was put down by Qin forces, Chen and Wu were assassinated by their own men.\n|[[File:Qin_Uprisings.png|100px]]\n|<ref>{{cite book|title=The Chinese Strategic Mind|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=LbgkCwAAQBAJ&pg=PA145&dq=Dazexiang+uprising#v=onepage&q=Dazexiang%20uprising&f=false|publisher=Edward Elgar Publishing|year=2015|author=Hong Liu|page=145}}</ref>\n|-\n|206 BC\n|[[Emperor Gaozu of Han#Insurrection against the Qin dynasty|Liu Bang's Insurrection]]\n|[[Qin dynasty|China]]\n|[[Han dynasty|Han forces]]\n|style=\"background:#AF9\"|The [[Qin dynasty]] is overthrown in a popular revolt and after a [[Chu\u2013Han Contention|period of contention]], Liu Bang is crowned Emperor of the [[Han dynasty]].\n|[[File:Qin_Uprisings.png|100px]]\n|\n|-\n|205\u2013185 BC\n|Great revolt of the Egyptians\n|[[File:Double_crown.svg|20px]] [[Ptolemaic Kingdom|Egypt]]\n|[[Egyptians]], led by [[Hugronaphor]] and [[Ankhmakis]]\n|style=\"background:#F88\"|Revolt put down by the [[Ptolemaic Kingdom]], cementing [[Greeks|Greek]] rule over Egypt.\n|[[File:Ptolemaic_Kingdom_III-II_century_BC_-_pt.svg|100px]]\n|<ref>{{cite web|url=http://english.cri.cn/1702/2005-4-29/14@232828.htm|title=The great revolt of the Egyptians (205\u2013186 BC)|accessdate=8 June 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160303233131/http://english.cri.cn/1702/2005-4-29/14@232828.htm|archive-date=3 March 2016|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n|-\n|